04174nam a22007095i 9780813543901DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20072007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135439017 a10.36019/97808135439012doi  a(DE-B1597)529762  a(OCoLC)1163877991  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBM674.79b.G83 2007 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a296.4/537109732221 aGubkin, Liora, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYou Shall Tell Your Children :bHolocaust Memory in American Passover Ritual /cLiora Gubkin. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b5  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Listening to Voices from the Killing Ground -- t1. Passover and the Challenge of Holocaust Memory -- t2. Collected Memories -- t3. Wrestling with Redemption -- t4. Anne Frank, Hope, and Redemption -- t5. Heroism Redeemed: The Warsaw Ghetto Uprising -- t6. Provisional Conclusions -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPassover is among the most widely observed holidays for American Jews. During this festival of redemption, Jewish families retell the biblical story of Exodus using a ritual book known as a haggadah, often weaving modern tales of oppression through the biblical narrative. References to the Holocaust are some of the most common additions to contemporary haggadot. However, the parallel between ancient and modern oppression, which seems obvious to some, raises troubling questions for many others. Is it possible to find any redemptive meaning in the Nazi genocide? Are we adding value to this unforgivable moment in history? Liora Gubkin critiques commemorations that violate memory by erasing the value of everyday life that was lost and collapse the diversity of responses both during the Shoah and afterward. She recounts oral testimonies from Holocaust survivors, cites references to the holiday in popular American culture, and analyzes examples of actual haggadot. Ultimately, Gubkin concludes that it is possible and important to make a space for Holocaust commemoration, all the time recognizing that haggadot must be constantly revisited and "performed."   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aHolocaust (Jewish theology) 0aHolocaust (Jewish theology). 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aJudaismxLiturgy. 0aSederxLiturgy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813543901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813543901.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK